Mincer earnings equation estimation¶

Our task is to construct model that explains wage income of bank's clients.

The available data consists of 42 groups of summary statistics (7 summary statistics in one group) about different aspects of cash spending/cash obtaining, that the clients undergoes during the last 6 months (also one variable equals to age).

The main purpose of this notebook is to explain individual predictions by the means of LIME.

To make explanations easier to understand, instead of using all the summary statistics, we will focus on the one time period (6 months spending/obtaining) monetary values. This will reduce the pool of variables to 43.

4.¶

First, we will compare LIME decompositions for different observations in the dataset. The predictive model is XGBoost.

Observation #1¶

Observation #2¶

Observation #3¶

The common variables appearing across decompositions are: total amount of expenses, age, salary. The most stable attribution is the total amount of expenses, as it is top1 in all of the observations.

5.¶

Now, we are going to make a second model, RandomForest, and find an observation for which LIME attributions are different in the relation to the previous XGBoost model.

It was kind of difficult to find any example that differs in the all 5 attributions, so we stopped our search when there were only two differences.

XGBoost¶

RandomForest¶

We see that the differences are in usage of variables: age, spending on public transport, property tax, total amount of client's income. In the non-differences, directions are the same, and values are also almost the same. Although the local models differ in 2 out of 5 attributions, the local predictions are almost as good as the global ones.

6. Summary¶

The method has high stability for the most predictive variables across the samples and, also the issue of finding an 'all different' example for two different models, suggests that it has also high stability for them across different models.

def train_test_split_by_income(data, test_size=0.2, bins=5):
    income_bined = pd.qcut(data['Y'], q=bins)

    return model_selection.train_test_split(data, test_size=test_size, shuffle=True, stratify=income_bined, random_state=SEED)

def as_pyplot_figure(self, label=1, **kwargs):
    """Returns the explanation as a pyplot figure.

    Will throw an error if you don't have matplotlib installed
    Args:
        label: desired label. If you ask for a label for which an
               explanation wasn't computed, will throw an exception.
               Will be ignored for regression explanations.
        kwargs: keyword arguments, passed to domain_mapper

    Returns:
        pyplot figure (barchart).
    """
    import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
    exp = self.as_list(label=label, **kwargs)
    fig = plt.figure(figsize=(16.9, 4.6), dpi=200)
    vals = [x[1] for x in exp]
    names = [x[0] for x in exp]
    vals.reverse()
    names.reverse()
    colors = ['green' if x > 0 else 'red' for x in vals]
    pos = np.arange(len(exp)) + .5
    plt.barh(pos, vals, align='center', color=colors)
    plt.yticks(pos, names)
    if self.mode == "classification":
        title = 'Local explanation for class %s' % self.class_names[label]
    else:
        title = f'Local explanation (intercept: {self.intercept[0]:.2f}, local pred: {self.local_pred[0]:.2f}, global pred: {self.predicted_value:.2f})'
    plt.title(title)
    plt.tight_layout()
    return fig
